{{Lacking ISBN|date=July 2014}}
'''Japanese dissidence during the early Shōwa period''' was [[dissident|dissidence]] by Japanese citizens of the [[Empire of Japan]] (1868–1947) during the [[Shōwa period]], the reign of the Shōwa Emperor, [[Hirohito]] (1926–1989). The early Shōwa period witnessed the rise of [[Japanese militarism]], and Imperial Japan's full-scale invasion of China in the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] (1937–1945), which escalated into a full-scale invasion of the [[Asia-Pacific]] during the [[Pacific War|Pacific theatre]] of [[World War II]] (1941–1945). Throughout the period, there was [[political repression in Imperial Japan]].

==History==
The [[Japanese Communist Party]] (JCP) was suppressed by the Imperial Japanese government.
Mass round ups took place on March 15, 1928, and were followed by mass round ups on April 16, 1929.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Japanese Communist movement, 1920-1966|author= [[Robert A. Scalapino]]|publisher= University of California Press|year= 1967 |pages= |isbn= }}</ref> In February 1930, the central committee of the Japanese Communist Party approved the formation of "red self-defense bodies".<ref>{{cite book |title= The Japanese Communist Party 1922-1945|author=  George M. Beckmann, Genji Okubo|publisher= Stanford University Press|year= 1969 |pages= 192–195|isbn= }}</ref>

The JCP protested against the Manchurian Incident.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Japanese Communist Party 1922-1945|author= George M. Beckmann, Genji Okubo|publisher= Stanford University Press|year= 1969 |pages= 220|isbn= }}</ref> Following the Manchurian Incident, the JCP continued anti-war activities.<ref>{{cite book |title= Japan's Total Empire: Manchuria and the Culture of Wartime Imperialism |author= Louise Young|publisher= University of California Press|year= 1999 |pages= 165–167|isbn= }}</ref>

The Party was finished by 1935.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Japanese Communist movement, 1920-1966|author= [[Robert A. Scalapino]]|publisher= University of California Press|year= 1967 |pages= |isbn= }}</ref> A communist party rebuilding committee was established, and was active until May 1941.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Japanese Communist Party 1922-1945|author=  George M. Beckmann, Genji Okubo|publisher= Stanford University Press|year= 1969 |pages= 261|isbn= }}</ref>

Several anarchist groups operated in Japan. The Black Youth League, or Kokuren, Farming Villages Youth Association, or Noseisha, and the Zenkoku Jiren. The Koto branch of the Tokyo general workers Union and the Tokyo Food Workers Union merged into the anarchist syndicalist union federation Libertarian Federal Council of Labour Unions of Japan, or Jikyo.<ref>{{cite book | title= Hatta Shūzō and Pure Anarchism in Interwar Japan | publisher= Macmillan| author= John Crump | year= John Crump| page= 87| isbn=}}</ref>

The Zenkoku jiren protested against the Manchurian Incident.<ref>{{cite book | title= Hatta Shūzō and Pure Anarchism in Interwar Japan | publisher= Macmillan| author= John Crump | year= John Crump| page= 69–172| isbn=}}</ref>

The split in Zenkoku Jiren led to a split of pure anarchists and anarchist syndicalists.<ref>{{cite book | title= Hatta Shūzō and Pure Anarchism in Interwar Japan | publisher= Macmillan| author= John Crump | year= John Crump| pages= 87–95| isbn=}}</ref> Zenkoku Jiren came to an end following the mass arrests of anarchists in 1935-1936.<ref>{{cite book | title= Hatta Shūzō and Pure Anarchism in Interwar Japan | publisher= Macmillan| author= John Crump | year= John Crump| page= 172| isbn=}}</ref> Anarchism was active in Japan until 1935.<ref>{{cite book | title= The Japanese Communist Party 1922-1945 | publisher= Stanford University Press | author= George M. Beckmann, and Genji Okubo | year= 1969 | page= 71 | isbn=}}</ref>

In 1933, the government suppressed a faculty and student protest in [[Kyoto Imperial University]]. The protest was in reaction to the government's suspension of Professor Yukitoki Takigawa from the university. This incident became known as the [[Takigawa incident]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Hatoyama Dynasty: Japanese Political Leadership Through the Generations | publisher=Palgrave Macmillan | author=Itoh, Mayumi | year=2003 | page=62 | isbn=9781403981523}}</ref>

In 1940, [[labor unions in Japan]] were dissolved, and replaced by the ultranationalistic [[Industrial Association for Serving the Nation]] (Sangyō Hōkokukai, or Sampō).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanfocus.org/-Christopher-Gerteis/4159|title=Political Protest in Interwar Japan Part I 戦間期日本の政治的抗議活動 「上」 :: JapanFocus|publisher=|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>

Japanese who went abroad went to countries such as the USSR,<ref>{{cite book | url=https://hermes-ir.lib.hit-u.ac.jp/rs/bitstream/10086/8312/1/HJsoc0320100010.pdf | last=Kato | first=Tetsuro | title=The Japanese Victims of Stalinist Terror in the USSR | journal=Hitotsubashi Journal of Social Studies | volume=32 | number=1 | date=July 2000 }}</ref> China,<ref>{{cite book | title= Dilemma in Japan | publisher= Little, Brown | author= Roth, Andrew | year= 1945 | pages= 162–192 | isbn=}}</ref> the United States, Mexico and France.<ref>{{cite book | title= Pacific Citizens: Larry and Guyo Tajiri and Japanese American Journalism in the World War II Era | publisher= University of Illinois Press | author= Greg Robinson| date= Feb 9, 2012 | pages= 94–97 | isbn=}}</ref>

In wartime Japan, only passive resistance, and insignificant protests occurred.<ref>{{cite book |title= Pacific War, 1931-1945 |publisher= Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group |author= Ienaga ,Saburo |year= 2010|pages= 203–228 | isbn=}}</ref> In 1943, the [[Sōka Gakkai]] were imprisoned for advising their followers not to buy amulets from the [[Grand Shrine of Ise]].<ref>{{cite book | title= Bibliography of Japanese New Religious Movements|publisher= Routledge|author= Peter B Clarke |date= Dec 16, 2013 |pages= 235| isbn=}}</ref>

[[Political prisoners in Imperial Japan]] were not released until the end of WWII.<ref>{{cite book |title= Allied Occupation of Japan| author= Takemae, Eiji |publisher= A&C Black|year= 2003|pages= 235–240|isbn= }}</ref>

